HEADWORD: Squalor
<hw>Squa"lor</hw> <pr>(skw⟦amac⟧"l⟦ocir⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.,
fr. <ets>squalere</ets> to be foul or filthy.]</ety> <def>Squalidness;
foulness; filthiness; squalidity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The heterogeneous indigent multitude, everywhere wearing nearly
the same aspect of <qex>squalor</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To bring this sort of <qex>squalor</qex> among the upper
classes.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

